Comment: Recall how demonetisation has met none of its stated, and shifting objectives, including controlling terrorists, black money and fake currency. Will Modi Govt., face same fate here of rewriting the political landscape of the country. Rajya Sabha approved the resolution abrogating Article 370 for J&K and a bill to bifurcate the state into two union territories, Jammu and Kashmir and Ladakh,  when mainstream leaders have been arrested, phone networks cut, Broadband internet and cable TV services entirely shut down and Section 144 of the CRPC enacted. How will revoking its special status affect the autonomy of the state? How will the bifurcation change the political landscape of the state? Modi Govt., has fulfilled its election promise without caring much for its objectives and purpose. With the Centre‚Äôs decision, political disagreement has also taken centre stage. However I sincerely wish Modi Govt. total success so that bloodshed can be avoided and integration with Kashmiri people may take place in true sense.

Title: LIVE: PM Modi Addresses the Nation on The Abrogation of Article 370 in Jammu and Kashmir
Comment:
In all parts of India, Modi Govt has totally failed to provide jobs. Four out of 10 youth who received vocational training are out of the labour force, and a significant chunk of those in the workforce remain unemployed. 1.8% of the population reported receiving formal  vocational/ technical training in 2017-18. 5.6% reported receiving informal vocational training (such as hereditary, self-learning, and on the job training). This means 93% of the population did not receive any vocational/technical training from either formal or informal sources. The youth (15-29 years) comprised more than half of the people who received formal  vocational/ technical training. On the whole, most youth remain outside the ambit of formal training, and many of those who undergo months of vocational training at their own cost remain jobless.¬†Although the PMKVY aims to provide training free of cost, most of the youth who have received formal training have had to bear the cost of training, the PLFS data shows. 
But does Modi Govt have an alternative plan? Modi's budget speech at least gave no indication that the government has a credible plan to address India‚Äôs unemployment challenge.

Title: LIVE: PM Modi Addresses the Nation on The Abrogation of Article 370 in Jammu and Kashmir
Comment:
It was easy for them to get jobs in Jammu and Kashmir since people of Jammu & Kashmir could not compete with them. ‚ÄúMaharaja Hari Singh was very much concerned about the issue
and in order to address the concern of Kashmiri pandits & Dogras, Mahraja Hari Singh enacted article 35 A under notification number I-L/84 on 20th April 1927 to define state subjects (Mulki) . ‚ÄúThe article gave Jammu and Kashmir a carte blanche to determine the ‚Äòpermanent residents‚Äô of the state & grant them special rights and privileges in state sector jobs, acquisition of property
within the state, public aid and welfare schemes. The notification I-L/84 classified four grades of ‚ÄúState Subjects‚Äù (Mulki). ‚ÄúClass I ‚ÄìThose persons who were born and residing in the state before the reign of Maharaja Gulab Singh and those who had settled and been permanently residing before 1885. Class II ‚Äì Those persons who had settled in the state before 1911 and also acquired
immovable property. ‚ÄúClass III ‚Äì Included those permanently residing in the state and who acquired any immovable property after ten years of continuous residence ‚ÄúClass IV ‚Äì Included those persons those not covered under Class I,II,III‚Äù.

Title: LIVE: PM Modi Addresses the Nation on The Abrogation of Article 370 in Jammu and Kashmir
Comment: Like Article 370 extended to other states. ‚ÄúArticle 371F ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Sikkim‚Äú‚Äú Article 371 G ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Mizoram ‚ÄúArticle 371 H ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Arunachal Pradesh‚Äú ‚ÄúArticle 371 I ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Goa ‚ÄúAll these provisions cater the needs of special circumstances that exist in those areas in order to provide the constitutional remedies for various socio-economic challenges. ‚ÄúIn the case of article 35 A the provision mandates that no act of the legislature coming under it can be challenged for violating the constitution. ‚ÄúIn 1920s during the rule of Mahraja Hari Singh, demands had been raised by the Kashmiri Pandits and Dogras that outsiders should not be allowed to settle in the state to take away the opportunities of acquiring property and government jobs. ‚ÄúAt that time people of west Punjab neighbouring Jammu and Kashmir were highly educated as compared to people of Jammu and Kashmir

Himachal Pradesh inspired by article 35-A also enacted law with similar nature that of Jammu and Kashmir. ‚ÄúBesides there are 11 states that have privilege of special status of similar nature with respect to Jammu and Kashmir.‚ÄúThe articles that accorded special status to other states are as follows.‚Äú‚Äú Article 371 ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Maharashtra and Gujarat ‚ÄúArticle 371A ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Nagaland ‚ÄúArticle 371 B ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Assam ‚ÄúArticle 371C ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Manipur ‚ÄúArticle 371D & 371 E ‚Äì Special provision with respect to Andhra Pradesh

Vedic Sanskrit alphabet have been modified to Devanagari and to simplest Gujanagari(Gujarati) script and yet Hindi is taught in a very printing ink wasting non cursive complex script to millions of children in India. Why not adopt a simple script at national level? Indian states can retain their languages, scripts and culture by teaching highly propagated Hindi/Sanskrit in regional scripts to impart technical education through a script converter or in India's simplest Gujanagari script along with a Roman script to revive Brahmi script.

Title: Yashwant Sinha On Article 370 & Jammu And Kashmir
Comment:
All we say that Drastic, Brute Force may rebound badly on us. In today era of Globalisation and Social Media, popular resentment is being seen and observed by everyone thru-out the world. We can't supress it. It would have been better had such decisions (Annulment of A370 and A35A) taken with confidence of a functional J&K Legislative Assembly for more legitimacy. We are trading in unchartered waters, so govt should be prepared for facing  repercussion. If we as Indian can condemn Human Rights Violation of Uighurs in Xinjiang Province, so does others can condemn of our actions on pretext of HR Violation. 

Also, don't forget about India's Position/Situation in the subcontinent because of Rising China and Geopolitics of the South Asia. 

Also, for God's Sake Don't Give it a communal colour. 

This issue opened the Pandora Box of Demand of Separate States which is a threat to Unity and Sovereignty of India. This is in reference to the speech of Mr. Biswajit Daimary (BPF Rajya Sabha Member from Assam) who supported the  Abrogation of A370 bill and Trifurcation of the State, and asked for similar Bifurcation of the State of Assam into Bodoland (bordering Bhutan) and Rest of Assam. If this trend continues that North East will become a mini Europe into 15-20 states alone. 

History is the witness that dialogue and non-violence can solve any problem, least you have perseverance and determination.

Comment:
Black Day for Indian Democracy: Majority of Indian are supporting Abrogation of Article 370 & Article 35A as they are not on the receiving end of such action. This will further increase the insecurities of the people of J&K.  People of rest of India can't supercede voice of People of J&K. Similarly,  all the Legislation concerning Protection of Rights of Indigenous People should be abrogated (like Reservations for Locals in AP, MH, KN, TN) for realising the Goal of Akhand Bharat.

Another reality is that we have become an intolerant society propelled by hypernationalism to such an extent that even so called "secular party" will stop dissenting to unconstitutional bills in fear of losing majority population support  in Election (Rahul Gandhi and  Dijvijay Singh stunt of proving a better Hindu than their counterparts). We should respect will of the people. How can we say that Abrogation of A370 is the will of the people when the Lok Sabha and Panchayat Election Voting percentage was 10% and 5% respectively in Kashmir Valley. The danger of a strong government is that it takes decision in a hurry and brute force rather than by consensus.

Title: Jammu & Kashmir Reorganisation Bill Passes in Rajya Sabha
Comment:
When Bernard Lewis put forward his thesis titled ‚ÄúBalkanisations of the Middle East‚Äù in 1992, he predicted that a trend that had shaped the world in the 20th Century would also be highly influential in the new century.

The last century went down in history as a period when radical nationalism divided countries, nations and regions. It is natural that everyone loves and wants to protect his own nation, but radical nationalism, which violates other people‚Äôs right to life and empowers itself through the oppression of others, brought a lot of pain to the world. Central Europe was divided into many small states. New borders were drawn for the Balkans. The map of the Arabian Peninsula changed significantly. The former Soviet Union was divided into dozens of new states. Africa, South America and Far East Asia all took their share of this new world order. The number of countries in the world, which was around 77 at the dawn of the 20th Century, reached approximately 200 by the end of it.

A large majority of these divisions were the result of a bloody process. Balkan peoples, who had been living together for 500 years, started fighting with each other. Millions of innocent lives were lost, and many more had to abandon their homes. When Central Europe was divided into small states, it laid the foundation for the Second World War. Civil wars and regional conflicts were constantly present in Asia and Africa due to the divisions. Warlords took control of the majority of these conflict zones. Mass murders and genocides followed one after another. The trend of division took millions of lives.

A change at this magnitude in the world political map has brought many problems with it. First of all, the seeds of hatred, the effects of which would last for decades, were sown among the sister communities that lived together for many years. Secondly, the divisions were followed by large waves of migration as millions of women, children and the elderly had to leave their homes. Another important problem was the unsolvable border disputes. Artificial borders, that have no historical, geographical or social foundation have become reasons for conflicts that often dragged the countries into a hot war.

The Indian subcontinent witnessed events that are similar to those happening in many other parts of the world. Today, the Bengal region, often referred to as a conflict zone, was one of the richest regions in the world not long but only 300 years ago. It had an economy of 90 billion USD and a population of 150 million. These figures corresponded to the 20% of the world gross national product and 25% of the world‚Äôs population. A sense of civilization with many architectural structures that symbolizes wealth, such as Taj Mahal, was prevalent in the region. The Babylonian Empire brought order, peace and wealth to the region.

In the 18th Century, the Empire was divided into small states and disintegrated. The British who came to the region a century ago for commercial purposes took control of the Indian subcontinent by establishing colonial governments and the region remained as a British colony for 200 years. The local people were considered as second-class citizens, and even as uncivilized, primitive beings, and were subjected to inconceivable cruelty. During this time, hundreds of thousands of Indians lost their lives in the occupation wars of the British. Millions of innocent people died of starvation in the four planned major famines. All the resources of a giant civilization built on an area of millions of square kilometers were seized by the colonists. (1)

After World War II, this vast area experienced yet another division. The country was divided as Pakistan, which had a Muslim majority, and India, which had a Hindu majority. Like every division of the 20th Century, India‚Äôs division was also bloody. More than one million lives were lost, 15 million people migrated. After independence, there have been three great wars between these two countries. The departure of the British was as bloody as their arrival in every region it occupied. In the same period, three million civilian lives were lost in the civil war in Pakistan. East Pakistan seceded from the country under the name of Bangladesh. (2)

The imperialist forces have invariably left behind never-ending conflict zones. These conflict zones were a means of keeping the regions where they physically withdrew under their control. Disagreements in the Northern Kashmir region continue to this day. The Muslim-populated region was left to Hindus during the division; it should have been obvious that such a decision would result in violence. India and Pakistan fought over Kashmir in 1947, 1965 and 1999. A referendum that could easily end the conflicts has never materialized nor is it likely to do so in the immediate future. The region is now divided into three de facto regions after their giant northern neighbor China entered into the equation.(3) At the end of the 1980‚Äôs, a new conflict emerged in the region in which 70,000 civilians died; about 8,000 civilians are missing. It is generally acknowledged that the missing persons are most likely to be found buried in mass graves, which are being discovered every day.(4)

It is impossible for violence of this magnitude to occur on its own. The atmosphere of conflict is the most important strategy of those who plan to divide other countries. In this way, they are able to call the shots behind closed doors, sell weapons, and control the economy. Most importantly, they can continue to utilize the region to accomplish their own aims. In the meantime, as always, it is the innocent people who suffer during this process as a nation‚Äôs energy is exhausted in endless conflicts. Violence occupies the region.

What needs to be done to bring peace to the region, especially to Kashmir, is to build a rational and temperate culture where all the peoples are treated as first-class citizens, instead of creating a political understanding based on conventional interests. In the case of Kashmir, it is unrealistic to think of a system that Pakistan is not involved with. Pakistan, unlike India, is a part of a great family, the Muslim world. Muslims are also the spiritual guardians of Kashmir. India is one of the countries that the Islamic world considers as a friend and a brother. India‚Äôs economic and political interests lie in its friendship with the Muslim world. No matter where, the contest of military prowess is always unwinnable and it will only cause more bloodshed. It is the friendship-based alliances that will render the countries stronger and allow people to live in prosperity. Such an alliance would create a deterrent force no weapon can provide. Pakistan and India do not need new weapons, but new alliances. It is the reign of peace in the region which will bring comfort to the people, not conflict.

Congratulations to BJP , Indians wanted this to happen years back but now proper governance has proved its capabilities.
I am from Kashmir and I am proud that the article has been abolished ...
Now we can live without fear , we can live with our heads high , we can now have better tourism , schools , opportunities & the fear of terrorism & our children who are pulled in it will vanish for good.. the article has always helped the terrorism to function in our beautiful land but now we can let our children move freely without fearing for  them to get brain washed.....
Many of our kashmiri ministers may loose some power & may be against it but as we locals know we couldn't say anything then but now it's going to be difficult for these traitors ... 
We Kashmiris are also proud indians but have been looked upon with hate due to few within us who have helped the cowards to kill innocent & our army men who have helped us in calamities these few people have shamed us but now we want good opportunities for our children , hard earned money & want our state to function in peace like other indian states ...
BJP we are with you now we won't get distracted on religious or minority votes we appeal our brothers and sisters to stand together at this hour and don't get brain washed and if thrs any news related to terrorism contact the army and police and fight to have a safe Kashmir .....
